CONCEPT
        websocket - The WebSocket Protocol (RFC 6455)

DESCRIPTION
        WebSocket is a protocol providing full-duplex communication channels
        over a single TCP connection. It is designed to be implemented in
        web browsers and web servers, but can be used by any client or
        server application.

        By enabling WebSocket support during compilation of the driver,
        web-based clients can connect directly to the mud without requiring
        an external proxy. WebSocket and telnet connections coexist on the
        same ports and in the same game simultaneously.

        The driver implements the WebSocket protocol as defined in RFC 6455.
        No external libraries are required.

        If the driver is compiled with WebSocket support there is a define
        __WEBSOCKETS__.

USAGE
        To use WebSocket support, configure your driver with
        enable_use_websockets=yes in your settings file.

        After starting the driver you have four new efuns:
        websocket_init_connection(), websocket_send(), websocket_close(),
        and websocket_query_state().

        There are two ways to establish a WebSocket connection:

        1) Auto-detection on any port

            When a new connection's first bytes match an HTTP GET request,
            the driver automatically enters the WebSocket handshake instead
            of telnet negotiation. This allows a single port to serve both
            telnet and WebSocket clients transparently.

            Once the WebSocket handshake completes, text frames are
            delivered as normal LPC commands (through catch_tell/input_to),
            and the connection behaves like any other interactive connection.
            The mudlib does not need to be aware of the transport protocol
            unless it wants to use WebSocket-specific features.

            To detect if a player is using WebSocket:

                #include <websocket.h>

                if (websocket_query_state(this_player()) == WS_ACTIVE)
                    // WebSocket client
                else
                    // telnet client

        2) Efun-initiated via websocket_init_connection()

            An existing interactive connection can be switched to WebSocket
            mode by calling websocket_init_connection(). This places the
            connection into a handshake state where it expects an HTTP
            upgrade request from the client. An optional completion callback
            can be specified.

        WebSocket Secure (WSS):

            To use secure WebSocket connections, establish TLS first using
            tls_init_connection(), then the WebSocket protocol operates
            over the encrypted TLS connection. The data flow is:

                Network <-> TLS <-> WebSocket <-> Command Processing

        Binary Data:

            Binary WebSocket frames are dispatched through the H_WEBSOCKET
            driver hook rather than normal command processing. This allows
            the mudlib to handle structured binary protocols (e.g., JSON-
            based game protocols, binary map data) separately from text
            commands.

            Use websocket_send() with the WS_BINARY opcode to send binary
            data to WebSocket clients:

                #include <websocket.h>

                websocket_send(data, WS_BINARY);

        Control Frames:

            Ping and Pong frames are handled automatically by the driver.
            The close handshake is also handled automatically, but can be
            initiated from LPC using websocket_close().

HISTORY
        Introduced in LDMud 3.6.9.

